    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1891-05-29T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1891-05-29T00:00:00-05:00" n="402" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d402">
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Chinese
                                    consul-general</gloss> to Mr. <persName type="to">Tsui</persName>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">San
                                        Francisco</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1891-05-29">
                            <hi rend="italic">May 29,
                                1891</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Two Chinese merchants and one student holding certificates issued by
                            Chinese consul at Yokohama properly viséed by American consul arrived
                            per steamship <hi rend="italic">City of Pekin</hi>. Collector refuses to
                            land them, mainly on the ground that Chinese consuls have no right to
                            issue certificate or passport to Chinese merchants or exempt class
                            residing at their ports to come to the United States. See Department on
                            the matter immediately. Steamer departs June 2.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Li Yung Yew</hi>,<lb/>
                        <hi rend="italic">Chinese Consul-General</hi>.</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
